Cyborg (Rewritten)

Target IP: 10.10.232.111
Challenge Description: A box involving encrypted archives, source code analysis and more.

Reconnaissance


I performed a TCP port scan against the target machine by running the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.232.111 -p- and obtained the result shown above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports. Time to perform an aggressive scan against these two TCP ports.


Running the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.232.111 -p 22,80 returns the result shown above. The scan identified the target machine is running Linux. The web server on port 80 is running Apache 2.4.18 and it seems to be serving the default Apache webpage. Time to enumerate the web application on port 80 first.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application. I viewed the source-code of the web application, but I did not find anything useful. Time to perform a directory search.


I performed a directory search by running the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.232.111/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt,pdf and obtained the result shown above. There are two interesting entries that stand out to me: /admin and /etc.


I browsed to /admin first and the webpage above was returned to me. This website is dynamic and there are clickable navigation buttons. I viewed the source-code and identified multiple interesting links including one to a file.


On the top of the website, I clicked on the Admins button and the webpage was returned to me. I obtained two useful usernames: josh and alex. Also, the message at 5.45am from Alex is vital. It mentions this user was messing around with squid proxy and all the config files are laying about. This user also mentions they have a backup file called music_archive lying around. If these files contain sensitive information, such as hardcoded credentials, it could lead to compromise.


At the top of the website, I noticed the Archives button. I clicked on this button and noticed another button called Download. Then a file called archive.tar was downloaded on my machine.


After extracting the content, I obtained the files shown above. I did not find anything important. However, the README contained the information This is a Borg Backup repository.. This ZIP archive looks like it was performed using Borg. I will need to install this on my machine and extract the contents properly.


I browsed to http://10.10.232.111/etc/ and the webpage above was returned to me. There is one accessible directory by the name /squid. Is this where the sensitive files are located, as mentioned by alex?


And bingo. When I browsed into the /squid, the webpage above was returned to me. There are two files here: passwd and squid.conf. Time to download these files to my machines and check their contents.

Exploitation

SSH Foothold as alex by Owning the Borg Backup File and Obtaining Hardcoded Credentials of user alex


The passwd file contains the entry shown above. The entry music_archive:$apr1$BpZ.Q.1m$F0qqPwHSOG50URuOVQTTn. is credentials. The password part is encrypted. Time to crack this.


I copied music_archive:$apr1$BpZ.Q.1m$F0qqPwHSOG50URuOVQTTn. to my machine to crack the password. I saved this content to a file called hash on my machine. Then I executed the command john hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt to crack the password and obtained the ciphertext squidward, as shown above.


To extract the contents of the borg backup, I ran the command borg extract home/field/dev/final_archive::music_archive as shown above. The passphrase I entered is squidward which I cracked earlier.


Then a new directory called alex was created after the extraction, as shown above.


Running the command tree shows the file note.txt that is inside Documents directory, as shown above. Running cat Documents/note.txt returns the hardcoded credentials alex:S3cretP@s3. Can I SSH into the target machine using this credentials? Time to find out.


And bingo! I SSHed into the target machine as the user alex and the password S3cretP@s3, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user alex. Time to elevate my privileges on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: Overwriting Public SSH Key of user root by Abusing Command Injection Vulnerability Inside /etc/mp3backups/backup.sh Script

Running the command sudo -l shows the script /etc/mp3backups/backup.sh can be executed with elevated privileges. I ran the command ls -la /etc/mp3backups/backup.sh to identify if I can edit this script, but I didn't have write privileges. Time to enumerate further.


The entire script is shown above. It looks like this script is vulnerable to command injection, especially the last parts of the script where the input is read and processed.


To test if the script is vulnerable to command injection, I executed the command sudo /etc/mp3backups/backup.sh -c whoami as shown above. And yep. I received the output root at the end of the execution of the script. Now obtaining a shell is super simple, as the payload sudo /etc/mp3backups/backup.sh -c /bin/bash can be used to spawn a root shell. However, running this resulted in the terminal hanging and the output from command execution was only displayed at end. Time to obtain a far more stable root shell. And this can be achieved by overwriting the authorized_keys of the user root by abusing the command injection flaw inside this backup.sh script.


On my machine, I ran the command ssh-keygen to generate the key pairs. I saved these as cyborg_root on my machine. After generating the SSH key pairs, I ran the command cat cyborg_root.pub to display the new key ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAINx06gHw6rNbh0SNFlIkY6qxjPcyqsDYvhsscbPozvsH kali@kali. I will need to overwrite the public SSH key (authorized_keys) of the user root.


I ran the command sudo /etc/mp3backups/backup.sh -c /bin/bash to open a root shell first. This spawns a root shell; however, the output from the command execution is not output until we exit from the root terminal session using exit. I ran the following commands to overwrite the key:

cd /root
mkdir .ssh
echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAINx06gHw6rNbh0SNFlIkY6qxjPcyqsDYvhsscbPozvsH kali@kali' >> authorized_keys
exit
cd /root
mkdir .ssh
echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAINx06gHw6rNbh0SNFlIkY6qxjPcyqsDYvhsscbPozvsH kali@kali' >> authorized_keys
exit


After exiting the session, time to connect to the target machine as the user root using cyborg_root key via SSH. And bingo! I ran the command ssh root@10.10.232.111 -i cyborg_root and obtained access on the target machine as the user root as shown above. Now I have a stable root shell with root privileges via SSH :)
